2.1	Risk Management Plan Executive Summary
The Executive Summary gives an overview of each of the components of the Risk Management Program, including:

¿	A narrative on the accidental release prevention and emergency response policies as required by 40 CFR 68.155(a);
¿	A description of the stationary source and regulated substances handled as required by 40 CFR 68.155(b);
¿	A section on general accidental release prevention and chemical-specific prevention steps as required by 40 CFR 68.155(c);
¿	The Five-Year Accident History of the facility as required by 40 CFR 68.155(d);
¿	A description of the emergency response program as required by 40 CFR 68.155(e); and
¿	A discussion of planned changes to improve safety as required by 40 CFR 68.155(f).  


The Executive Summary to be included in RMP*eSubmit is shown in its entirety in Section 2.1.1 to 2.1.7 below.

2.1.1	Introduction and Policies
Flint Hills Resources Alaska LLC (FHRA) is owner and operator of a petroleum facility in North Pole, Alaska (the Facility). FHRA purchased this facility in April 2004 from Williams Alaska Petroleum, Inc. Since doing so, FHRA has gone to great efforts to further develop and prioritize health and safety performance at the facility. At FHRA, safety is a value. As such, it defines who FHRA is and what FHRA believes in. The facility has made a commitment to both employee and public safety. FHRA's vision is to be recognized as a leader for safe operations ensuring the health and safety of employees, contractors, customers, and neighbors. FHRA's first priority is prevention. This priority is demonstrated by the resources FHRA has invested in accident prevention.  These include designing and constructing equipment to meet stringent, nationally recognized standards of performance. FHRA operates and maintains equipment to ensure reliability, which also serves as a measure of how safe an operation is. FHRA trains employees to recognize the importance of safety and to incorpora
